    <h1>Financial Assistance</h1>
    <h2>State Programs</h2>
<p>If you live in Massachusetts, you may be able to get health insurance or help paying your health care bills through a state program like <a title="MassHealth" href="https://www.mass.gov/topics/masshealth" target="_blank">MassHealth</a>, the <a title="Health Connector" href="https://www.mahealthconnector.org/" target="_blank">Health Connector</a>, or <a title="Health Safety Net" href="https://www.mass.gov/orgs/health-safety-net" target="_blank">Health Safety Net</a>.&nbsp;Each program has different rules and income limits.&nbsp;</p>
<p>To find out more and apply:</p>
<ul>
<li>Visit a patient financial counselor at your hospital or health center, or</li>
<li><a class="arrow-red class" title="Mass Health Connector website" href="http://www.MAhealthconnector.org" target="_blank"> Go to www.MAhealthconnector.org</a></li>
</ul>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h2>Discounts</h2>
<p>If you have medical bills because you do not have insurance, or because your health insurance did not cover your care, you may qualify for a discount. A <a title="paper application" href="/Assets/Documents/For-Patients/Financial-Assistance-Billing/Partners-Financial-Assistance-Application.pdf" target="_blank">paper application</a> along with supporting documentation may be required. Patients are required to apply for any available State Programs before being considered for Financial Assistance.There are&nbsp;three types of discounts:</p>
<ol>
<li>If your bills are for an emergency or other medically necessary services and your household income is below 301% of the Federal Poverty Guide, you may qualify for a discount ranging from 70 to 100% for acute care if you do not qualify for any state programs. Your qualifications and amount of discount depends on the type of care provided and your individual circumstances including&nbsp; your household income.*<br /><br />
<p><a class="arrow-red class" title="Financial Assistance Application" href="/Assets/Documents/For-Patients/Financial-Assistance-Billing/Partners-Financial-Assistance-Application.pdf" target="_blank">Download the financial assistance application to apply for this discount.</a></p>
</li>
<li>If your bills are from Spaulding or McLean, then you may be able to get a 60% to 100% discount if you do not qualify for any state programs.&nbsp;In most cases this determination is made prior to your receiving care at those facilities. The discount amount will depend on your household income.*<br /><br />
<p><a class="arrow-red class" title="Financial Assistance Application" href="/Assets/Documents/For-Patients/Financial-Assistance-Billing/Partners-Financial-Assistance-Application.pdf" target="_blank">Download the financial assistance application to apply for this discount.</a></p>
</li>
<li>You may get a 25% discount on any medical bills if you pay (or set up a payment plan) within 2 months of the date on your first bill.&nbsp;This does not apply to bills from Rehabilitation Network or McLean Hospital&nbsp;</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Important</strong>: Many health care bills are for co-payments, co-insurance, or deductibles that are required as part of your health insurance.&nbsp;We&nbsp;DO NOT discount those bills.&nbsp;<sub><br /></sub></p>
<p><a class="arrow-red class" title="Financial Assistance Screening Tool" href="/for-patients/Patient-Billing-Financial-Assistance/Financial-Assistance/Screening-Tool.aspx">Find out if you qualify for any of these discounts by using this screening tool.</a></p>
<p><em>*If you qualify for a financial assistance discount, you will never pay more than what the average insurance company would pay. Discount rates are reassessed annually and may change.</em></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h2>Payment Plans</h2>
<p>You may set up a zero interest monthly payment plan for any bill, even a bill for a health insurance co-payment, co-insurance, or deductible. Payment plans are limited to terms of 1 year for balances up to $1,000 and two years for balances over $1,000.</p>
</div>

